ACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#1B1B37>10:19:59 pm</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Jpegs, gradients, and quality.</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">well, i have some trouble here, when i finsh a pic, and happen to use heavy gradients, i save it as a max quality jpeg, but when i see it on the board, it looks like crap!<br>
<br>
well, any solutions or suggestions?<br>
<br>
(as i write this, i figured that perhaps i'm relying too much on the gradient, and should use the airbrush.)</font><P><P><i></i></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR=#aaaaaa><TD NOWRAP width=20% valign=top align=left><B><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2><A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ufuschnick.showPublicProfile?language=EN>FuSchnick</A></FONT></B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Member</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#1B1B37>2/23/01</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#1B1B37>11:32:15 pm</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Stuff</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Well, you probably already know that JPG is a lossy compression scheme... just like MP3, it achieves really good compression (like 90% or more) at the cost of some accuracy.<br>
<br>
Smooth gradients are a &quot;worst case scenario&quot; for the methods of compression that JPG uses.  The format excels in noisy pictures, which real photos usually are.  But lineart, cartoons, or &quot;simple&quot; art get the shaft.<br>
<br>
If your picture is 256 colors or less (line-art or flat-shaded) then GIF would be best.  It compresses pretty good and has no loss at all.  The limiting factor is the 256 color limit, which also doesn't work well for smooth gradients.<br>
<br>
PNG might be better, it is very similar to gif but allows more colors (how many I'm not sure exactly).  It is not lossy either.</font><P><P><i></i></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR=#CCCCCC><TD NOWRAP width=20% valign=top align=left><B><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2><A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/utumultuary.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tumultuary</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www16.brinkster.com/tumultuary/logo.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></FONT></B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Member</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#1B1B37>2/24/01</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#1B1B37>4:38:02 pm</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT><BR><img src=http://www16.brinkster.com/tumultuary/reallysmiley.jpg width=110 height=85></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Re: Jpegs, gradients, and quality.</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">No, he's saying that no matter how high he sets the quality, it ends up banded.<br>
<br>
Some graphics programs lie and don't actually let you set stuff to theoretical max. You might want to change programs.</font><P><div align="right"><embed src="http://www.geocities.com/psychic_weatherman/ultraflag.swf" width="180" height="120" wmode=transparent></div><P><i></i></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR=#aaaaaa><TD NOWRAP width=20% valign=top align=left><B><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2><A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ushousetsu.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Shousetsu</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.newelysium.com/forum/psicon.gif width=13 height=13 BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></FONT></B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Moderator</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#1B1B37>2/24/01</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#1B1B37>5:02:52 pm</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT><BR><img src=http://www.newelysium.com/forum/persphoto.jpg width=80 height=60></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Re: Jpegs, gradients, and quality.</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Colors high in saturation/contrast will do that when saving a JPG. Its best to stay away from them.</font><P><a href="http://www.newelysium.com"><img src="http://www.newelysium.com/banners/newelysium.gif" border=0></a><P><i></i></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR=#CCCCCC><TD NOWRAP width=20% valign=top align=left><B><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2><A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/une0xl.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ne0xl</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://forgotten.port5.com/icon.jpg BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></FONT></B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Member</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#1B1B37>2/25/01</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#1B1B37>3:08:04 pm</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT><BR><img src=http://forgotten.port5.com/me.jpg width=150 height=189></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Re: Jpegs, gradients, and quality.</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">The reason they get messed up when you view them is because browsers lower the quality even more then the original so it will load faster.<br>
